title: note-halting-problem
summary: Turing's proof (1936) that no general algorithm can determine whether an arbitrary program will halt or run forever
tags: HistoryOfComputing
year: 1936
period: Computability Theory

Proved by reduction to a contradiction: if a halting-detector existed, you could construct a program that does the opposite of what it predicts, causing it to be wrong. The result established that there are well-defined computational problems that are //provably unsolvable// — not just hard, but impossible. This was the first clear boundary on the power of computation.
